        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Idempotency"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An idempotent operation produces the same result whether it is called once or many times. In an agentic tool chain this matters because network failures, model retries, and user re-runs can all cause the same tool call to execute more than once. Without idempotency, those duplicate executions cause duplicate charges, duplicate emails, duplicate database rows — problems that are hard to undo and hard to explain."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Idempotency: Safe vs Unsafe Retry — two-panel diagram showing a double charge without a key and a cached result with a key",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Rule of thumb: any tool that writes to external state — charge a card, send a message, create a record — must be idempotent. Tools that only read data are naturally idempotent."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "HTTP Method Idempotency"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "HTTP defines idempotency semantics at the method level. Understanding these semantics helps you decide whether a given API call is safe to retry automatically."
          }
        ]
      },
