      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Idempotency Keys"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "An idempotency key is a unique identifier the caller attaches to a request. The server stores the result against that key and returns the cached result for any subsequent request that carries the same key. Stripe, Braintree, Plaid, and many other payment APIs support this pattern natively via an "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Idempotency-Key"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " HTTP header."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import uuid\nimport requests\n\ndef create_payment_intent(\n    amount_cents: int,\n    currency: str,\n    customer_id: str,\n    idempotency_key: str | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Create a Stripe PaymentIntent.\n\n    Pass the same idempotency_key on retry to avoid double-charging.\n    Generate one key per logical charge and store it before the first call.\n    \"\"\"\n    if idempotency_key is None:\n        idempotency_key = str(uuid.uuid4())\n\n    resp = requests.post(\n        \"https://api.stripe.com/v1/payment_intents\",\n        auth=(\"sk_live_...\", \"\"),\n        data={\n            \"amount\": amount_cents,\n            \"currency\": currency,\n            \"customer\": customer_id,\n        },\n        headers={\"Idempotency-Key\": idempotency_key},\n        timeout=10,\n    )\n    if resp.status_code == 200:\n        return {\"ok\": True, \"intent\": resp.json(), \"idempotency_key\": idempotency_key}\n    return {\n        \"error\": \"PAYMENT_ERROR\",\n        \"status\": resp.status_code,\n        \"message\": resp.json().get(\"error\", {}).get(\"message\", resp.text),\n        \"idempotency_key\": idempotency_key,\n    }\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Returning "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "idempotency_key"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in the response lets the caller log and reuse it if a retry is needed, without generating a new one that would create a fresh charge."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Server-Side Idempotency Cache"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When you build tool handlers that execute write operations, implement your own idempotency cache so that the tool itself is safe to retry — regardless of whether the downstream service supports idempotency keys."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import time\nimport threading\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import Any\n\n@dataclass\nclass _CacheEntry:\n    result: Any\n    created_at: float\n\n_IDEM_CACHE: dict[str, _CacheEntry] = {}\n_CACHE_TTL = 3600          # keep results for 1 hour\n_CACHE_LOCK = threading.Lock()\n\ndef _get_cached(key: str) -> Any | None:\n    with _CACHE_LOCK:\n        entry = _IDEM_CACHE.get(key)\n        if entry and time.time() - entry.created_at < _CACHE_TTL:\n            return entry.result\n        if entry:\n            del _IDEM_CACHE[key]   # expired\n    return None\n\ndef _cache_result(key: str, result: Any) -> None:\n    with _CACHE_LOCK:\n        _IDEM_CACHE[key] = _CacheEntry(result=result, created_at=time.time())\n\ndef send_invoice_email(\n    order_id: str,\n    customer_email: str,\n    idempotency_key: str,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Send an invoice email exactly once per idempotency key.\"\"\"\n    cached = _get_cached(idempotency_key)\n    if cached is not None:\n        return {**cached, \"idempotent_replay\": True}\n\n    # Perform the actual send\n    try:\n        result = _do_send_email(customer_email, order_id)\n    except Exception as exc:\n        # Do NOT cache failures — allow a genuine retry\n        return {\"error\": \"EMAIL_ERROR\", \"message\": str(exc)}\n\n    _cache_result(idempotency_key, result)\n    return result\n\ndef _do_send_email(to: str, order_id: str) -> dict:\n    # Calls the real email API\n    return {\"ok\": True, \"message_id\": f\"msg_{order_id}\"}\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Two critical rules: cache only successful results (failures should be retryable), and use a TTL long enough for the retry window but short enough to avoid stale entries consuming memory."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Generating Keys in the Agent Loop"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The model must generate and persist idempotency keys "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "before"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the first attempt so the same key can be reused on retry. A common pattern is to derive the key from the logical intent, making it deterministic rather than random."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import hashlib\nimport anthropic\n\nclient = anthropic.Anthropic()\n\ndef make_idempotency_key(*parts: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Stable key derived from the logical identity of the operation.\"\"\"\n    raw = \"|\".join(str(p) for p in parts)\n    return hashlib.sha256(raw.encode()).hexdigest()[:32]\n\n# Example: the key is stable across retries because it depends only\n# on the order and the logical action, not on time or randomness.\ndef refund_order_tool(order_id: str, reason: str) -> dict:\n    key = make_idempotency_key(\"refund\", order_id)\n    cached = _get_cached(key)\n    if cached:\n        return {**cached, \"idempotent_replay\": True}\n\n    try:\n        result = _issue_refund(order_id, reason)\n    except Exception as exc:\n        return {\"error\": \"REFUND_ERROR\", \"message\": str(exc)}\n\n    _cache_result(key, result)\n    return result\n\ndef _issue_refund(order_id: str, reason: str) -> dict:\n    return {\"ok\": True, \"refund_id\": f\"ref_{order_id}\", \"reason\": reason}\n\n# Agent loop usage\ntools = [\n    {\n        \"name\": \"refund_order\",\n        \"description\": \"Issue a refund for an order. Safe to retry — idempotent.\",\n        \"input_schema\": {\n            \"type\": \"object\",\n            \"properties\": {\n                \"order_id\": {\"type\": \"string\"},\n                \"reason\": {\"type\": \"string\"},\n            },\n            \"required\": [\"order_id\", \"reason\"],\n        },\n    }\n]\n\ndef run_agent(user_message: str) -> str:\n    messages = [{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": user_message}]\n    while True:\n        resp = client.messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n            max_tokens=1024,\n            tools=tools,\n            messages=messages,\n        )\n        if resp.stop_reason == \"end_turn\":\n            return next(b.text for b in resp.content if hasattr(b, \"text\"))\n        messages.append({\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": resp.content})\n        results = []\n        for block in resp.content:\n            if block.type == \"tool_use\":\n                result = refund_order_tool(**block.input)\n                results.append({\n                    \"type\": \"tool_result\",\n                    \"tool_use_id\": block.id,\n                    \"content\": str(result),\n                })\n        messages.append({\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": results})\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Deriving the key from "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "(\"refund\", order_id)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " means a retry for the same order always produces the same key, regardless of how many times the model calls the tool."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Handling Concurrent Requests"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In a multi-threaded or async environment, two concurrent requests can arrive with the same key before the first one completes. A simple dict cache is not enough — you need a lock that prevents the second request from executing the write while the first is still in flight."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import threading\n\n_IN_FLIGHT: dict[str, threading.Event] = {}\n_IN_FLIGHT_LOCK = threading.Lock()\n\ndef idempotent_execute(key: str, fn, *args, **kwargs) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"\n    Execute fn(*args, **kwargs) exactly once for a given key.\n    Concurrent callers with the same key wait for the first to finish.\n    \"\"\"\n    with _IN_FLIGHT_LOCK:\n        cached = _get_cached(key)\n        if cached is not None:\n            return {**cached, \"idempotent_replay\": True}\n        if key in _IN_FLIGHT:\n            event = _IN_FLIGHT[key]\n        else:\n            event = threading.Event()\n            _IN_FLIGHT[key] = event\n            event = None   # this thread is the executor\n\n    if event is not None:\n        # Wait for the executing thread to finish, then return from cache\n        event.wait(timeout=30)\n        cached = _get_cached(key)\n        if cached:\n            return {**cached, \"idempotent_replay\": True}\n        return {\"error\": \"SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE\", \"message\": \"concurrent execution timed out\"}\n\n    # This thread executes the operation\n    try:\n        result = fn(*args, **kwargs)\n        _cache_result(key, result)\n        return result\n    except Exception as exc:\n        return {\"error\": \"EXECUTION_ERROR\", \"message\": str(exc)}\n    finally:\n        with _IN_FLIGHT_LOCK:\n            ev = _IN_FLIGHT.pop(key, None)\n        if ev:\n            ev.set()\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The event-based approach serializes concurrent calls for the same key without blocking unrelated keys."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Idempotency in Database Writes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For tools backed by a relational database, store the idempotency key in the same table as the operation and use a unique constraint. The database then enforces exactly-once semantics atomically."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# SQLAlchemy example (PostgreSQL / SQLite)\nfrom sqlalchemy import Column, String, Integer, UniqueConstraint, create_engine\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import DeclarativeBase, Session\n\nclass Base(DeclarativeBase):\n    pass\n\nclass Refund(Base):\n    __tablename__ = \"refunds\"\n    id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True)\n    order_id = Column(String, nullable=False)\n    amount_cents = Column(Integer, nullable=False)\n    reason = Column(String)\n    idempotency_key = Column(String, nullable=False, unique=True)\n\nengine = create_engine(\"sqlite:///payments.db\")\nBase.metadata.create_all(engine)\n\ndef create_refund_db(\n    order_id: str,\n    amount_cents: int,\n    reason: str,\n    idempotency_key: str,\n) -> dict:\n    with Session(engine) as session:\n        existing = session.query(Refund).filter_by(\n            idempotency_key=idempotency_key\n        ).first()\n        if existing:\n            return {\n                \"ok\": True,\n                \"refund_id\": existing.id,\n                \"idempotent_replay\": True,\n            }\n        refund = Refund(\n            order_id=order_id,\n            amount_cents=amount_cents,\n            reason=reason,\n            idempotency_key=idempotency_key,\n        )\n        try:\n            session.add(refund)\n            session.commit()\n            return {\"ok\": True, \"refund_id\": refund.id}\n        except Exception:\n            session.rollback()\n            # Race condition: another thread inserted first\n            existing = session.query(Refund).filter_by(\n                idempotency_key=idempotency_key\n            ).first()\n            if existing:\n                return {\"ok\": True, \"refund_id\": existing.id, \"idempotent_replay\": True}\n            raise\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The unique constraint on "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "idempotency_key"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " makes the database the source of truth. Even if the in-memory cache is cleared (process restart, horizontal scaling), the database prevents duplicate refunds."
          }
        ]
      },
